      Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s economicsWe talked a  couple of  times last we=
ek about the plucky and successful=C2=A0activist campaign that hedge fund E=
ngine No. 1 LLC waged against Exxon Mobil Corp. I wrote on Thursday:Actuall=
y it=E2=80=99s a little mysterious to me what=E2=80=99s in it for Engine No=
. 1? As we discussed yesterday, it owns 917,400 shares of Exxon stock and s=
pent about $30 million on the proxy fight. It bought that stock in mid-Nove=
mber and early December, when Exxon was trading at around $37 or $38 per sh=
are; it closed yesterday at $58.94. Figure the fund is up about $21 per sha=
re, and has collected another $1.74 per share in dividends, and you get a g=
ross profit of maybe $21 million; after proxy-fight expenses that=E2=80=99s=
 a loss of $9 million. Perhaps now that its nominees are on the board, Exxo=
n will change strategy and add a lot of long-term value and make Engine No.=
 1 rich. Or perhaps there are some other economics that I=E2=80=99m missing=
. But it=E2=80=99s not obvious to me how this trade =E2=80=94 spend $35 mil=
lion on stock and $30 million on a proxy fight =E2=80=94 makes a lot of eco=
nomic sense. Maybe they just did it for the good of the planet.Well! About =
a hundred of you emailed me to say that it=E2=80=99s obvious what=E2=80=99s=
 in it for Engine No. 1: publicity. This is a hedge fund that launched six =
months ago; it runs a small fund and doesn=E2=80=99t have much of a track r=
ecord. Now it is=C2=A0The Little Engine That Took Down Exxon. It has=C2=A0g=
one from nothing to being a daring successful activist, and=C2=A0an activis=
t with a halo of environmental virtue. It can fundraise off of that forever=
, attract lots of money, collect lots of fees, etc. The $30 million of prox=
y expenses are an investment to make millions more in management fees.A rel=
ated benefit is what any activist fund gets from a successful proxy fight: =
The=C2=A0next=C2=A0company they go after will be intimidated by their Exxon=
 victory,=C2=A0and will try to settle by giving them board seats. You spend=
 $30 million on one proxy fight so you don=E2=80=99t have to spend any mone=
y on five more. You show up at a meeting with the next company=E2=80=99s CE=
O, you put Exxon=E2=80=99s severed head on the table, you say =E2=80=9Cboar=
d seats, now,=E2=80=9D and you get them without a fight.=C2=A0Fine! That=E2=
=80=99s all fair enough. One reader pointed out another, more technical but=
 also quite important answer: It is customary for activist hedge funds that=
=C2=A0win=C2=A0their proxy fights to be=C2=A0reimbursed by the company.[1] =
So, because it won, Engine No. 1 probably spent $30 million of Exxon=E2=80=
=99s money on the proxy fight, not its own. That probably helps. It took a =
big=C2=A0risk=C2=A0here: If it had lost the proxy fight, it would be out $3=
0 million and wouldn=E2=80=99t have all the fundraising benefit of having t=
aken down Exxon. But because it won, the economics actually look pretty goo=
d.Elsewhere in the Exxon proxy fight:Asset manager State Street Corp voted =
for two of the four candidates put forward by activist hedge fund Engine No=
. 1 for Exxon Mobil's board, a spokesman for the Boston firm said late on T=
hursday.State Street was Exxon's third-largest investor according to its pr=
oxy statement. Late on Wednesday Exxon's largest investor Vanguard Group sa=
id it also backed two dissident nominees, details that fleshed out how Engi=
ne No. 1 was able to capture at least two board seats at the biggest U.S. o=
il producer.When we talked about the proxy fight last week, I used BlackRoc=
k Inc. as an example of a big index-y Exxon shareholder that wants companie=
s to care more about climate change and supported Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s pu=
sh for a more renewables-focused Exxon. BlackRock is Exxon=E2=80=99s second=
-biggest shareholder, loves to  talk=C2=A0about sustainability, and release=
d a =E2=80=9Cvote bulletin=E2=80=9D last week saying=C2=A0that it would be =
voting for three of Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s director candidates; it was the =
most obvious example. But the other two =E2=80=9CBig Three=E2=80=9D index-y=
 shareholders also voted for change. The lesson here is that if you are a s=
mall activist looking to run a proxy fight to push a big company in an envi=
ronmental/social/governance direction, you might be able to pick up some bi=
g allies. Also:In the hours leading up to this week=E2=80=99s annual shareh=
olders meeting, Exxon went to extraordinary lengths to head off the threat =
from a campaign about which it had been largely dismissive months earlier.E=
xxon telephoned investors the morning of the ballot -- and even during an u=
nscheduled, hour-long pause during the virtual meeting -- asking them to re=
consider their votes, according to several of those who received calls. Som=
e said they found the last-ditch outreach and halt to the meeting unorthodo=
x and troubling.=E2=80=9CIt was a very unusual annual general meeting,=E2=
=80=9D said Aeisha Mastagni, a fund manager at the California State Teacher=
s=E2=80=99 Retirement System, a major Exxon investor that backed the activi=
st campaign from the beginning. =E2=80=9CIt didn=E2=80=99t feel good as an =
investor.=E2=80=9DI think the basic reading here is that at a giant public =
company like Exxon, the managers and board of directors sort of assume that=
 they get to decide who can be on the board, and that shareholders are not =
really supposed to interfere. Technically this assumption is wrong, and at =
Exxon last week it did not work out, but you can see why Exxon found it so =
surprising.AMCJust  a great trade here:AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. gain=
ed Tuesday, extending last week=E2=80=99s rally, after raising $230.5 milli=
on with a stock sale to Mudrick Capital Management as the movie-theater ope=
rator pledged to =E2=80=9Cgo on offense=E2=80=9D with acquisitions.The agre=
ement with New York-based Mudrick is for 8.5 million shares of common stock=
 at $27.12 apiece, 3.8% more than Friday=E2=80=99s closing price, AMC said =
Tuesday in a statement. The company, now an icon among retail traders, jump=
ed as much as 23% to $32 at the open in New York trading. It traded at $29.=
98 at 9:35 a.m.The latest equity sale with Mudrick =E2=80=9Csounds expensiv=
e=E2=80=9D with debt and equity indicating an enterprise value of over $16 =
billion, Michael Pachter of Wedbush said in an email to Bloomberg. If it re=
turns to pre-Covid levels, AMC could optimistically reach around $1 billion=
 in earnings after adjustments. The highest attained in the past is $929 mi=
llion in 2018, he said. =E2=80=9CMudrick must know something I don=E2=80=99=
t.=E2=80=9DHere=E2=80=99s a thing Mudrick knows:Mudrick=E2=80=99s stock pur=
chase comes with the caveat that the shares be =E2=80=9Cfreely-tradeable=E2=
=80=9D, meaning the firm could sell the shares at any point or in any size =
it chooses. That would provide Mudrick with 8.5 million shares that could b=
e sold as soon as today.Here are the press release=C2=A0and the prospectus =
for Mudrick=E2=80=99s potential sales. (Don=E2=80=99t miss the  GameStop-st=
yle risk factors, which include: =E2=80=9CWithin the last seven business da=
ys, the market price of our Class A common stock has fluctuated from an int=
ra-day low of 12.05 on May 21, 2021 to $36.72 on May 28, 2021, and we have =
made no disclosure regarding a change to our underlying business during tha=
t period.=E2=80=9D) I have no idea what Mudrick is actually doing; all I am=
 saying is that this is not a trade that ought to work under traditional th=
eories, but it=E2=80=99s very much a trade that works now:=09A meme stock c=
loses on Friday at $26.12 per share, up 116% on the week on no particular n=
ews (but with   lots of talk about short squeezes).=09You buy stock from th=
e company over the holiday weekend=C2=A0at a premium.=09You announce it on =
Tuesday morning.=09Everyone says =E2=80=9Coh wow good news for that meme st=
ock, guess the wild rally is going to continue.=E2=80=9D=09So it does.=09Yo=
u sell the stock=C2=A0into the enormous volume and rising prices on Tuesday=
 morning.Like imagine the negotiations over the price. It is traditional, w=
hen one investor buys a big chunk of stock from a company, for the investor=
 to get a bit of a discount. Here, though, the premium helps Mudrick: It ma=
kes the stock sale less dilutive, signals confidence in the stock, feels li=
ke a win. So the stock goes up even more and, if Mudrick=C2=A0does=C2=A0wan=
t to sell immediately, it can do so at a profit.=C2=A0I wonder if banks are=
 pitching AMC on bought-deal stock offerings. I wonder what price they=E2=
=80=99re pitching. The traditional answer, for a volatile and meme-y stock,=
 would be that you=E2=80=99d want a healthy discount to account for all of =
the risk you take in reselling the stock: =E2=80=9CWe are confident in AMC =
and so can offer you a bought deal at a tight discount, down just 5% from y=
esterday=E2=80=99s close.=E2=80=9D But the right answer is actually a healt=
hy premium.


